WEBVTT

00:00:09.730 --> 00:00:13.920
Hi, I'm John Geleynsse, Director of
Technology Evangelism at Apple.

00:00:14.260 --> 00:00:17.100
With more and more apps on
the App Store every day,

00:00:17.210 --> 00:00:20.420
it's important to take your app
to the next level to get noticed.

00:00:20.600 --> 00:00:23.560
In this video,
I'll show you some great apps

00:00:23.560 --> 00:00:27.560
on the App Store today that
set new standards in usability,

00:00:27.560 --> 00:00:29.600
design, and innovation.

00:00:29.700 --> 00:00:33.870
These examples will help you to
understand the characteristics and key

00:00:33.870 --> 00:00:36.600
ingredients that make apps really great.

00:00:36.640 --> 00:00:38.600
So let's get started.

00:00:38.820 --> 00:00:41.890
Here are the seven ingredients that
we've seen in some of the best apps on

00:00:41.890 --> 00:00:46.770
the App Store and as we've worked with
countless developers creating apps for

00:00:46.780 --> 00:00:49.600
iPhone and iPad over the past few years.

00:00:49.600 --> 00:00:54.010
As you design and create your iOS app,
be sure to incorporate as many

00:00:54.010 --> 00:00:56.410
of these ingredients as possible.

00:00:56.590 --> 00:00:58.600
Let's look at these one by one.

00:00:58.600 --> 00:01:02.530
First of all, great iPhone and iPad
apps are delightful.

00:01:02.890 --> 00:01:05.280
They draw you in,
they keep you satisfied,

00:01:05.280 --> 00:01:07.600
and leave you with a great experience.

00:01:07.600 --> 00:01:10.600
Making you come back again and again.

00:01:10.600 --> 00:01:13.600
Delightful apps do this in several ways.

00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:15.600
First, they're inviting.

00:01:15.600 --> 00:01:20.300
They have an attractive design that
leaves a great first impression.

00:01:20.600 --> 00:01:25.590
So be sure that your app leaves a
great first impression with users.

00:01:26.160 --> 00:01:28.700
Delightful apps are also intuitive.

00:01:28.840 --> 00:01:32.220
This means that people know
exactly what to do when they first

00:01:32.280 --> 00:01:36.000
launch them and never need to
consult a manual or any other help.

00:01:37.330 --> 00:01:41.060
Intuitive apps are designed with
users in mind and they're organized

00:01:41.060 --> 00:01:43.280
in ways that meet user expectations.

00:01:44.180 --> 00:01:48.250
So the question is this:
is your app intuitive or is it

00:01:48.360 --> 00:01:50.640
difficult for people to use?

00:01:50.810 --> 00:01:53.360
Delightful apps are also engaging.

00:01:53.550 --> 00:01:57.270
This means that they keep
people coming back for more.

00:01:57.430 --> 00:02:01.810
Your app should meet a need so
effectively and provide so much value

00:02:02.180 --> 00:02:05.110
that users come back again and again.

00:02:05.270 --> 00:02:07.600
Delightful apps are also enabling.

00:02:07.690 --> 00:02:11.720
Meaning they allow people to do
things they couldn't do before.

00:02:11.830 --> 00:02:14.150
I mean, think about this for a moment.

00:02:14.380 --> 00:02:16.190
How will your app do this?

00:02:16.380 --> 00:02:21.800
How will your app do what it does in
a way that's never been done before?

00:02:21.990 --> 00:02:25.060
And finally,
delightful apps are exciting.

00:02:25.140 --> 00:02:27.900
This means they generate
enthusiasm in people,

00:02:27.940 --> 00:02:32.040
they have flair,
and they show great attention to detail.

00:02:32.160 --> 00:02:35.150
And in my experience,
apps in any category of the

00:02:35.150 --> 00:02:37.040
App Store can be exciting.

00:02:37.170 --> 00:02:40.890
Here's a great example of
a very inviting casual game

00:02:40.890 --> 00:02:43.360
called Dizzy B by Igloo Games.

00:02:43.450 --> 00:02:46.620
This app leaves you with a
very happy first impression.

00:02:46.710 --> 00:02:50.000
It's attractive,
has bright and friendly colors,

00:02:50.100 --> 00:02:53.760
very cute sounds, and is very responsive.

00:02:53.840 --> 00:02:56.300
And a whole lot of fun to play.

00:02:56.390 --> 00:02:59.340
And keep in mind,
these are really valuable

00:02:59.340 --> 00:03:02.800
attributes to have,
even if your app isn't a game.

00:03:02.940 --> 00:03:06.340
Here's another really inviting
game called Carcassonne.

00:03:06.450 --> 00:03:09.980
It's just like the real board game,
which many families and

00:03:09.980 --> 00:03:11.540
friends like to play.

00:03:11.620 --> 00:03:14.840
If you've ever played the real
board game and then discovered

00:03:14.840 --> 00:03:18.520
this app on the App Store,
you won't be disappointed.

00:03:18.590 --> 00:03:22.020
Carcassonne for iPad uses
high-quality textures and visual

00:03:22.020 --> 00:03:25.700
elements from the real board
game that look fantastic on iPad.

00:03:26.010 --> 00:03:29.180
The production value of your
app's artwork should be as

00:03:29.180 --> 00:03:31.220
high-quality as possible,
too.

00:03:31.270 --> 00:03:34.860
And, wherever possible,
your app should mimic the real world

00:03:35.220 --> 00:03:38.860
or try to reflect elements of what
people are used to when they're

00:03:38.860 --> 00:03:40.840
doing the things your app does.

00:03:40.900 --> 00:03:43.200
Here's Time Tuner by Dream Surface.

00:03:43.250 --> 00:03:45.540
It's a bedside clock radio
with location-awareness,

00:03:45.550 --> 00:03:47.980
and it's also a great way
to get your app to work.

00:03:47.980 --> 00:03:49.980
It's also a great way
to get your app to work.

00:03:49.980 --> 00:03:51.980
It's also a great way
to get your app to work.

00:03:51.980 --> 00:03:53.980
It's a great way to get your app to work.

00:03:53.980 --> 00:03:57.980
It's a great app that's super
intuitive and does one thing so well,

00:03:58.120 --> 00:04:01.980
it could become a replacement for
the real thing for some people.

00:04:02.240 --> 00:04:07.940
Your app should do one thing well
and not try to do too many things.

00:04:08.240 --> 00:04:10.960
Now,
here's an example of an engaging app.

00:04:11.010 --> 00:04:12.920
Remember,
engaging means that the app keeps

00:04:12.970 --> 00:04:15.120
you coming back again and again.

00:04:15.190 --> 00:04:17.660
This is Tab Toolkit by Agile Partners.

00:04:17.710 --> 00:04:20.520
It won an Apple Design Award in 2010.

00:04:20.580 --> 00:04:24.380
It lets you download and sync tablature
files from the web to your iPad,

00:04:24.430 --> 00:04:29.120
and then use them to learn how to
play a piano or chord a guitar.

00:04:29.190 --> 00:04:32.110
It looks like sheet music,
and yet offers the ability

00:04:32.110 --> 00:04:34.840
to change instruments,
change tempo,

00:04:34.900 --> 00:04:38.600
isolate left hand or right hand,
bass guitar or lead guitar,

00:04:38.670 --> 00:04:40.720
and much more.

00:04:40.790 --> 00:04:44.990
And it's these capabilities,
combined with lots of valuable content,

00:04:44.990 --> 00:04:47.340
that keep users coming back for more.

00:04:48.040 --> 00:04:52.480
So what will your app do to be sticky
and bring people back time and again?

00:04:52.660 --> 00:04:55.700
And finally,
here's an example of an exciting app.

00:04:55.840 --> 00:04:59.320
It's the Jamie Oliver 20-Minute
Meals app for iPhone.

00:04:59.470 --> 00:05:02.580
It too won an Apple Design Award in 2010.

00:05:02.740 --> 00:05:06.530
It lets you pick great recipes,
manage their ingredients,

00:05:06.580 --> 00:05:09.490
organize grocery lists,
watch streaming videos,

00:05:09.750 --> 00:05:12.280
and follow detailed
step-by-step instructions.

00:05:12.670 --> 00:05:15.420
And the visual design of this
app is really attractive.

00:05:15.750 --> 00:05:17.790
Great production value.

00:05:17.950 --> 00:05:22.180
It's nicely organized and it uses
the latest technologies on iOS.

00:05:22.370 --> 00:05:24.600
That's what great apps do.

00:05:24.760 --> 00:05:28.520
But what sets this app apart
is its attention to detail.

00:05:28.730 --> 00:05:33.320
Because when you're following a recipe
step-by-step and then rotate the iPhone,

00:05:33.510 --> 00:05:35.830
you get a larger,
more legible presentation

00:05:35.830 --> 00:05:37.020
of instructions.

00:05:37.220 --> 00:05:39.820
And then,
if you tap the screen on the left,

00:05:40.020 --> 00:05:44.120
you get a photo of how the food should
appear at that stage in the recipe.

00:05:44.190 --> 00:05:45.820
I mean, how cool is that?

00:05:45.980 --> 00:05:47.700
That's not what you'd expect.

00:05:47.920 --> 00:05:51.000
And as a result,
it surprises and excites.

00:05:51.220 --> 00:05:53.580
Great apps sweat the details.

00:05:53.750 --> 00:05:57.200
So how will your app
exceed user expectations?

00:05:57.410 --> 00:06:00.660
So that's Delightful,
the first of seven essential

00:06:00.690 --> 00:06:02.930
ingredients for great apps.

00:06:02.950 --> 00:06:04.920
Great iPhone and iPad
apps are innovative.

00:06:06.240 --> 00:06:13.000
By innovation I mean groundbreaking,
jaw-dropping, category defining.

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:17.920
I mean really inspirational apps and
apps that are a breath of fresh air.

00:06:18.580 --> 00:06:20.700
Take Flight Control by FireMint.

00:06:20.780 --> 00:06:24.550
It's a highly addictive air traffic
control app which is used multi-touch

00:06:24.880 --> 00:06:28.190
to allow you to tap an incoming
airplane and drag a path to the

00:06:28.340 --> 00:06:30.290
runway matching the airplane's color.

00:06:30.500 --> 00:06:33.630
If two planes are going to collide,
you can tap one of them

00:06:33.900 --> 00:06:35.250
and drag a new flight path.

00:06:35.470 --> 00:06:40.500
It's simple to learn, easy to play,
and super addictive.

00:06:40.640 --> 00:06:44.010
Now, the innovative thing about
this app is that at the moment

00:06:44.010 --> 00:06:46.990
it arrived on the App Store,
it defined a completely

00:06:46.990 --> 00:06:48.500
new genre of gaming.

00:06:49.420 --> 00:06:51.620
Until then,
no one had ever done an app with

00:06:51.620 --> 00:06:53.380
that type of interaction model.

00:06:55.030 --> 00:06:59.140
Your goal should be to create
a genre-defining app too.

00:06:59.230 --> 00:07:01.870
Here's another really great
example of an innovative app.

00:07:02.130 --> 00:07:07.310
This is Peaks by Augmented Outdoors,
an app that lets you identify mountains

00:07:07.630 --> 00:07:11.580
by triangulating iPhone's GPS location,
compass bearing,

00:07:11.670 --> 00:07:15.580
and accelerometer to accurately determine
which direction you're looking and

00:07:15.580 --> 00:07:17.400
how far away you are from a mountain.

00:07:17.400 --> 00:07:20.860
It then tells you the name, height,
and distance of the

00:07:20.940 --> 00:07:22.980
mountain you're looking at.

00:07:23.070 --> 00:07:23.860
How cool is that?

00:07:24.750 --> 00:07:27.390
Before iOS and the App Store,
we couldn't imagine these

00:07:27.390 --> 00:07:29.340
types of innovative solutions.

00:07:29.340 --> 00:07:33.930
And now there are more and more augmented
reality apps every day transforming

00:07:33.930 --> 00:07:38.350
how we use our iPhones and iPads and
changing the way we get things done.

00:07:39.810 --> 00:07:43.410
How will you take advantage of similar
hardware and software features of iPhone,

00:07:43.490 --> 00:07:46.700
iPad and iOS to augment
what your app does?

00:07:46.700 --> 00:07:50.000
Here's an augmented
reality app for golfers.

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:53.700
This is Golfscape by
ShotZoom Software LLC.

00:07:53.990 --> 00:07:58.520
Hold this app up as you look down the
fairway and it will tell you how far

00:07:58.520 --> 00:08:02.550
away the green is and what obstacles
and traps exist and where they are.

00:08:03.500 --> 00:08:04.180
Amazing!

00:08:04.890 --> 00:08:07.700
Great apps exceed users' expectations.

00:08:07.910 --> 00:08:08.700
Yours should too.

