00:11:14.300 --> 00:11:17.410
So the question is this:
What innovations will

00:11:17.410 --> 00:11:19.060
you build into your app?

00:11:19.150 --> 00:11:22.210
Now, let's talk about optimization.

00:11:22.740 --> 00:11:26.400
Great iPhone and iPad
apps are also optimized.

00:11:26.410 --> 00:11:28.450
Now optimization means several things.

00:11:29.080 --> 00:11:32.700
First, it means that great
apps are high quality.

00:11:32.700 --> 00:11:34.700
This means they function as designed.

00:11:34.900 --> 00:11:35.690
They're robust.

00:11:35.690 --> 00:11:36.870
They're stable.

00:11:37.200 --> 00:11:38.700
They're reliable.

00:11:38.700 --> 00:11:42.340
They're just what people
expect on iPhone and iPad.

00:11:42.900 --> 00:11:46.240
Optimization also means
that you make sure your app

00:11:46.320 --> 00:11:48.730
delivers maximum performance.

00:11:48.800 --> 00:11:52.060
It launches quickly,
it's really responsive,

00:11:52.220 --> 00:11:54.580
and it's super efficient.

00:11:54.670 --> 00:11:59.610
Optimization also means optimizing your
app's integration with iOS technologies.

00:11:59.930 --> 00:12:03.880
That means using as many of the powerful
built-in frameworks as you can to

00:12:03.880 --> 00:12:08.720
deliver rich functionality rather than
writing your own duplicate frameworks.

00:12:08.790 --> 00:12:11.910
And here are some of the frameworks
available to your app on iOS,

00:12:12.010 --> 00:12:14.350
but there are many,
many more within the SDK.

00:12:14.640 --> 00:12:18.540
These frameworks are what we use
to develop iOS itself and what we

00:12:18.540 --> 00:12:22.640
use for built-in apps like Safari,
Mail, Photos, and more.

00:12:22.710 --> 00:12:26.840
These are mature, stable,
hardware accelerated.

00:12:26.930 --> 00:12:30.720
They're localized and accessible,
so using them means your app

00:12:30.720 --> 00:12:32.580
will be these things too.

00:12:32.640 --> 00:12:36.720
Lastly, optimizing your app means
building something that's

00:12:36.720 --> 00:12:38.520
made specifically for iOS.

00:12:38.590 --> 00:12:43.860
And targeted at the iPhone or iPad,
rather than developing something

00:12:43.970 --> 00:12:46.790
that's cross-platform and
lowest common denominator.

00:12:46.950 --> 00:12:51.400
Now here's a great example of an
app designed specifically for iPad.

00:12:51.480 --> 00:12:55.400
It's Infinity Blade by
Chair Entertainment Group.

00:12:55.490 --> 00:13:00.400
It has incredible gameplay,
unbelievable performance,

00:13:00.640 --> 00:13:03.480
and stunning high-res graphics.

00:13:03.580 --> 00:13:08.320
This is an app that's only possible
because it was developed for iPad.

00:13:08.580 --> 00:13:12.120
Here's another example of an app
designed specifically for iPad.

00:13:12.260 --> 00:13:15.020
This is Inkling,
an interactive textbook app that

00:13:15.340 --> 00:13:19.000
offers students interactivity,
social collaboration,

00:13:19.070 --> 00:13:22.760
tutorials and quizzes,
and simple ease of use,

00:13:22.760 --> 00:13:24.900
only possible on iPad.

00:13:25.090 --> 00:13:28.080
And then there's The Elements
by Theodore Gray,

00:13:28.200 --> 00:13:33.450
an interactive periodic table of the
Elements textbook offering content not

00:13:33.450 --> 00:13:38.100
previously available in digital form.

00:13:38.240 --> 00:13:38.910
for iPad.

00:13:53.970 --> 00:13:57.410
So the challenge is this:
be sure to optimize your app in

00:13:57.410 --> 00:13:59.620
all of the ways we just mentioned.

00:13:59.670 --> 00:14:03.780
Avoid just building something
and hoping it's good enough.

00:14:03.830 --> 00:14:05.640
Now, onto connected.

00:14:05.770 --> 00:14:11.110
Great iPhone and iPad apps are connected,
and there are three aspects to this.

00:14:11.370 --> 00:14:15.260
The first is to ensure that your
app works well with other apps.

00:14:15.310 --> 00:14:18.450
If your app displays a telephone number,
people should be able to tap

00:14:18.450 --> 00:14:22.300
that number and initiate a
phone call if they're on iPhone.

00:14:22.490 --> 00:14:25.500
If your app displays a web address,
people should be able to view that

00:14:25.640 --> 00:14:29.790
content within your app using a UI web
view or be automatically sent to

00:14:29.790 --> 00:14:32.640
Safari to browse the content there.

00:14:32.740 --> 00:14:36.340
And the same concept applies to street
addresses and other location information.

00:14:36.430 --> 00:14:40.330
Either display this information
within your app using Map Kit or allow

00:14:40.430 --> 00:14:43.000
people to switch out to the Maps app.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:46.600
The second aspect of
connectedness is to ensure that,

00:14:46.600 --> 00:14:48.870
where appropriate,
your app is connected with

00:14:48.960 --> 00:14:51.790
the personal information
available on the user's device.

00:14:51.900 --> 00:14:54.940
Contacts,
photos and more can be used by your app,

00:14:55.040 --> 00:14:57.900
making it far more
integrated and personal.

00:14:57.900 --> 00:15:01.260
And the third aspect of being connected,
and the focal point for this

00:15:01.380 --> 00:15:04.540
section of the presentation,
is that your app can reach out beyond

00:15:04.540 --> 00:15:07.890
itself to add more value for people.

00:15:08.840 --> 00:15:11.300
For example,
there are millions of iPhones out

00:15:11.400 --> 00:15:13.580
there that your app can connect to.

00:15:13.730 --> 00:15:15.100
Here's the Starbucks app.

00:15:15.170 --> 00:15:17.700
It looks great and
it's super easy to use.

00:15:17.770 --> 00:15:20.090
Among other things,
it lets you create your

00:15:20.090 --> 00:15:23.260
favorite Starbucks drink,
so that when your colleague, friend,

00:15:23.260 --> 00:15:24.940
or family member is
making a Starbucks run,

00:15:24.940 --> 00:15:28.700
you can connect to their iPhone
and send them your drink order.

00:15:28.980 --> 00:15:31.440
This is a simple example of
how to connect with others

00:15:31.830 --> 00:15:33.690
for a very practical reason.

00:15:33.840 --> 00:15:37.700
And it's a clever way of getting
people to notice and remember your app.

00:15:37.950 --> 00:15:40.750
Could your app benefit from being
able to do a digital handshake

00:15:40.750 --> 00:15:42.690
and exchange information this way?

00:15:42.940 --> 00:15:44.700
Here's iPad to iPad.

00:15:44.750 --> 00:15:47.500
I mentioned this app before,
it's Scrabble from Electronic Arts.

00:15:47.930 --> 00:15:50.790
But it's a great example
not only of innovation,

00:15:50.940 --> 00:15:54.270
but of connectedness between
iPads via Bluetooth or Wi-Fi to

00:15:54.540 --> 00:15:56.700
really enhance the gameplay.

00:15:56.900 --> 00:16:00.300
Connecting your app on iPhone with
a companion app on Mac OS X can

00:16:00.570 --> 00:16:02.700
also add lots of value for people.

00:16:02.700 --> 00:16:06.700
Here's Billings Touch by Market Circle.

00:16:06.700 --> 00:16:10.440
This is a very capable time tracking
app for anyone who wants to manage

00:16:10.490 --> 00:16:12.700
billing against projects or clients.

00:16:12.820 --> 00:16:15.700
On its own, it's really great.

00:16:16.220 --> 00:16:20.460
But combined with a companion app on
the Mac called Billings Mac OS X means

00:16:20.460 --> 00:16:24.260
people can have data automatically
synced so that they can take advantage

00:16:24.280 --> 00:16:28.890
of the power of the desktop to,
for example, design and print an invoice.

00:16:29.090 --> 00:16:32.310
And a similar example,
this time between iPhone,

00:16:32.310 --> 00:16:35.990
iPad and the Mac,
is Things by Cultured Code,

00:16:35.990 --> 00:16:39.890
a very flexible,
really well designed GTD getting

00:16:39.890 --> 00:16:44.410
things done to do manager app which
automatically synchronizes tasks and

00:16:44.520 --> 00:16:48.370
projects between these devices directly,
providing users with excellent

00:16:48.370 --> 00:16:49.760
functionality and mobility.

00:16:49.780 --> 00:16:52.900
This is definitely an
example worth following.

00:16:53.680 --> 00:16:56.890
And this is SkyGrid,
a great app with consistently high app

00:16:56.890 --> 00:17:01.290
store ratings that keeps people up to
date on the things that they care about.

00:17:01.300 --> 00:17:06.350
This app on iPhone and iPad is a great
example of how reaching out beyond the

00:17:06.350 --> 00:17:09.270
device can add lots of value for users.

00:17:11.540 --> 00:17:14.800
And the last example is
Flight Board by Ben Cazaz,

00:17:14.840 --> 00:17:18.750
an app that provides flight departure
and arrival information using a really

00:17:18.750 --> 00:17:21.500
accurate reproduction of a flight board.

00:17:21.530 --> 00:17:23.980
It's a simple,
extremely well done example of

00:17:24.040 --> 00:17:27.610
an app that reaches out beyond
the device to connect with more

00:17:27.610 --> 00:17:30.690
information of value to users.

00:17:31.910 --> 00:17:34.200
That's connected.

00:17:34.330 --> 00:17:35.800
Now, number five.

00:17:35.970 --> 00:17:39.280
Great iPhone and iPad
apps are accessible.

00:17:39.820 --> 00:17:43.860
Building accessibility in your app means
that everyone will be able to use it,

00:17:43.980 --> 00:17:47.180
which is important whether your app
is for in-house use by employees

00:17:47.580 --> 00:17:50.320
or for anyone in the app store.

00:17:50.620 --> 00:17:53.650
Now here are some interesting
stats for the US that are likely

00:17:53.650 --> 00:17:56.580
similar to the rest of the world.

00:17:56.760 --> 00:18:00.990
First of all,
10 million people are visually impaired.

00:18:02.580 --> 00:18:07.800
31 million people are hearing impaired.

00:18:07.800 --> 00:18:10.820
And some 12 million have
a learning disability.

00:18:10.840 --> 00:18:14.020
For example, they might have dyslexia and
so will misinterpret what they

00:18:14.090 --> 00:18:16.450
see on the screen in your app.

00:18:18.010 --> 00:18:22.860
So, all told, that's one in five users.

00:18:22.860 --> 00:18:25.340
Or one in five employees.

00:18:25.410 --> 00:18:28.130
Or one in five of your customers.

00:18:28.150 --> 00:18:33.060
Basically, 50 million people who won't be
able to use your app at all or

00:18:33.060 --> 00:18:37.440
who will have difficulty using
it unless you make it accessible.

00:18:37.790 --> 00:18:42.140
The good news is that accessibility
is built into iOS and integrated

00:18:42.140 --> 00:18:46.180
into numerous frameworks,
including UIKit, for example.

00:18:46.310 --> 00:18:50.080
Your job is to simply follow the
documentation and add accessibility

00:18:50.080 --> 00:18:52.530
wherever you can to your app.

00:18:53.220 --> 00:18:56.000
And in return,
the Accessibility Framework will enable

00:18:56.210 --> 00:19:02.680
powerful new capabilities in your app,
including voiceover and much more.

00:19:02.830 --> 00:19:07.680
Great iPhone and iPad apps are
accessible so that everyone can use them.

00:19:09.490 --> 00:19:12.740
Great iPhone and iPad apps are localized.

00:19:12.800 --> 00:19:17.480
It's more important than ever for your
app to be usable by people everywhere,

00:19:17.550 --> 00:19:21.170
since the App Store is now
in more than 90 countries.

00:19:21.360 --> 00:19:24.540
We live in a global village with many,
many languages being

00:19:24.540 --> 00:19:26.180
spoken in each country.

00:19:26.210 --> 00:19:29.140
Reaching all of these people in
their language of choice is a great

00:19:29.140 --> 00:19:33.040
way to make sure that your app
has as broad a reach as possible.

00:19:33.520 --> 00:19:37.400
So localize your UI for as
many languages as possible.

00:19:37.590 --> 00:19:39.910
Here's things for
iPhone by Cultured Code,

00:19:39.910 --> 00:19:44.270
available in English, German, and French.

00:19:44.650 --> 00:19:47.330
and even more languages.

00:19:47.330 --> 00:19:50.620
Localization can be restricted
to the basic UI of your app,

00:19:50.740 --> 00:19:52.840
but can extend to all
of your content too,

00:19:52.840 --> 00:19:54.490
if that makes sense.

00:19:54.510 --> 00:19:58.000
Every little bit helps,
and iOS makes it easy to include all of

00:19:58.000 --> 00:20:02.570
the translations within the same binary,
so that there's still only one

00:20:02.570 --> 00:20:04.500
app that users need to download.

00:20:06.910 --> 00:20:10.340
And finally,
great iPhone and iPad apps are designed.

00:20:10.480 --> 00:20:14.300
This means focusing on delivering
the optimal interaction design,

00:20:14.480 --> 00:20:17.800
meaning how the app works and what
happens when things are tapped.

00:20:18.050 --> 00:20:22.320
And focusing on a strong visual design,
meaning how the app looks

00:20:22.320 --> 00:20:24.460
and presents information.

00:20:25.400 --> 00:20:29.690
Let's begin with a great
quote by Adam Angst.

00:20:29.690 --> 00:20:33.420
He says,
"The iPad becomes the app you're using.

00:20:33.500 --> 00:20:37.300
Switch to another app and
the iPad becomes that app.

00:20:37.420 --> 00:20:40.290
If that's not magic,
I don't know what is." I love this

00:20:40.290 --> 00:20:44.310
quote because it's been my own
experience and it provides a great

00:20:44.310 --> 00:20:47.050
backdrop for a discussion on design.

00:20:47.170 --> 00:20:50.250
Here are a few examples
that illustrate this point.

00:20:51.310 --> 00:20:53.760
Here's maps on iPad.

00:20:53.810 --> 00:20:57.150
iPad becomes a digital map.

00:20:58.470 --> 00:21:00.980
Here's Notes on iPad.

00:21:00.980 --> 00:21:04.800
iPad becomes a classic paper notepad.

00:21:04.990 --> 00:21:06.440
Here's Calendar app.

00:21:06.550 --> 00:21:09.110
iPad becomes a day timer.

00:21:09.940 --> 00:21:11.380
Here's Contacts.

00:21:11.400 --> 00:21:13.580
iPad becomes an address book.

00:21:13.620 --> 00:21:18.060
Notice there's no menu bar,
no windowing system, no file system,

00:21:18.180 --> 00:21:21.700
or any of the encumbrances of a
traditional computing experience.

00:21:21.720 --> 00:21:25.770
The only thing that matters
is the app that's running.

00:21:26.790 --> 00:21:29.900
This is NPR, National Public Radio,
for iPad.

00:21:29.960 --> 00:21:34.700
It combines their radio broadcasts
with their excellent online content.

00:21:34.700 --> 00:21:39.700
iPad becomes the best
NPR experience ever.

00:21:40.630 --> 00:21:43.620
And here's a point of sale system
called Square for iPhone and

00:21:43.620 --> 00:21:48.290
iPad that's really attractive,
easy to use, and allows anyone to take

00:21:48.290 --> 00:21:49.500
credit card payments.

00:21:49.500 --> 00:21:53.500
Totally transformative
for small business.

00:21:54.310 --> 00:21:56.690
iPad becomes a point of sale system.

00:21:56.840 --> 00:21:59.910
Here's Marvel Comics,
a fantastic digital comic

00:22:00.010 --> 00:22:02.410
reading experience on iPad.

00:22:02.560 --> 00:22:05.640
iPad becomes a comic book.

00:22:06.330 --> 00:22:10.200
And here's AmpliTube Fender
by Agile Partners.

00:22:10.250 --> 00:22:15.100
iPad becomes a Fender guitar
amp and effects modeler.

00:22:15.250 --> 00:22:17.580
How beautiful is that?

00:22:18.930 --> 00:22:22.570
And so, as you can see,
each app takes over the iPad screen

00:22:22.930 --> 00:22:24.930
and the device becomes your app.

00:22:25.470 --> 00:22:28.140
It becomes whatever you want it to be.

00:22:28.280 --> 00:22:29.990
This is why design matters so much.

00:22:30.290 --> 00:22:34.270
It's vital that your app works
exactly as users would expect it to,

00:22:34.320 --> 00:22:37.960
and that it has the attention
to detail and polish needed

00:22:37.960 --> 00:22:40.290
to surprise and delight.

00:22:42.240 --> 00:22:46.260
These are the seven ingredients
of great iPhone and iPad apps.

00:22:46.370 --> 00:22:47.640
So there you go.

00:22:47.720 --> 00:22:50.420
There are definitely many more
app examples I could have talked

00:22:50.520 --> 00:22:53.940
about since there are lots of
really great apps on the App Store.

00:22:54.060 --> 00:22:57.700
And there are probably other valuable
ingredients we could discuss too.

00:22:57.810 --> 00:23:01.000
But the ones I've covered here
are the ones you should begin

00:23:01.000 --> 00:23:03.300
incorporating into your app today.

00:23:03.360 --> 00:23:06.730
I look forward to seeing the next
great version of your app and hearing

00:23:06.740 --> 00:23:12.060
about any questions you have and about
your experience developing for iOS.